summary:
14. Reiterates the importance of ensuring children's access to basic services during and after conflict.

15. Indicates willingness to consider assessing the impact of sanctions on children and minimizing unintended consequences.

16. Welcomes regional initiatives to protect children and urges them to:
    (a) Establish child protection units;
    (b) Include child protection staff in operations and provide training;
    (c) Curb cross-border activities harming children;
    (d) Allocate resources for children;
    (e) Integrate a gender perspective;
    (f) Declare initiatives to prohibit the use of child soldiers.

17. Encourages efforts to release abducted children and facilitate family reunification.

18. Urges strengthening national institutions and local civil society to ensure sustainability of local initiatives.

19. Calls for encouraging young persons' involvement in peace consolidation and peace-building.

20. Encourages the Secretary-General to include observations on child protection in his reports.

21. Requests a report on the implementation of this resolution and resolution 1261 by 31 July 2001.

22. Decides to remain actively seized of this matter.
